In [65]:
fname_oddball = "/home/FB/fb05/sassenha/experiments/ingmar/oddball_1.vhdr"
fname_rsvp = "/home/FB/fb05/sassenha/experiments/ingmar/rsvp_1.vhdr"
refchans = ["M1", "M2"]
def get_raw(fname):
    with mne.io.brainvision.read_raw_brainvision(fname, montage=montage_file, preload=True) as raw:
        raw.resample(100, n_jobs=24)
        raw.bads = [raw.ch_names.index("F3")]
        raw.interpolate_bads(reset_bads=True, mode='accurate')
        mne.io.add_reference_channels(raw, "FCz", copy=False)
        mne.io.set_eeg_reference(raw, ref_channels=[], copy=False)
        raw.apply_proj()
        m = mne.channels.montage.read_montage(montage_file)
        mne.channels.montage._set_montage(raw.info, m)
        mne.io.set_eeg_reference(raw, ref_channels=["M1", "M2"], copy=False)
        raw.filter(.1, 30, method='iir')
    return raw

from jr import auc_scorer
gat = GAT(predict_method="predict_proba", scorer=auc_scorer)

Generalizing P3 decoders to P6 experiment (violation vs. control sentence)¶

In [62]:
gat.predict_mode = "mean-prediction"
gat.predict(epochs2);
gat.score(y=epochs2.events[:, 2] > 100);
gat.plot();
gat.plot_diagonal(chance=.5);

We observe impressive above-chance decoding when generalizing between conditions. However, the neural patterns appears later in the P6 than the P3 contrast.
